&gt; Subject: [junit] Newbie questions
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Hello all
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m new to the unit testing world and I&#39;ve been learning from 
&gt; this two last weeks how to use the JUnit framework; so far I 
&gt; have no problems with the simple projects I&#39;ve made, but now 
&gt; I&#39;m a bit stumped. I develop over a set of frameworks which 
&gt; give me the skeleton for many of the classes I make. From it 
&gt; I can add my own code. In such cases, the classes inherit 
&gt; from a parent class where some kind of initialization is 
&gt; made. Well, is my understand that the test classes that I can 
&gt; make using JUnit have to set up the fixture using instance 
&gt; variables, but in my case I already have the set up made due 
&gt; to the parent initialization and I would like to take 
&gt; advantage of it. So, I tried to do the reverse: I made an 
&gt; inner class which extends TestCase within the class I want to 
&gt; test. But then I can&#39;t use the automatic way to create suites 
&gt; because JUnit doesn&#39;t extract the testMethods from the inner class.
&gt; This is a little example of one of my tries:
&gt; 
&gt; public class MyClass extends ParentClass {
&gt;       private String name;
&gt;       public MyClass( String name ) {
&gt;             this.name = name;
&gt;       }
&gt;       public String name() {
&gt;             return &quot;I am a &quot; + name;
&gt;       }
&gt; 
&gt;       public static void main( String[] ar ) {
&gt;             MyClass aThing = new MyClass( &quot;thing&quot; );
&gt;             // Problem: This parameter isn&#39;t accepted by the 
&gt;             // compiler.
&gt;             junit.textui.TestRunner( MyClass$TestMyClass.class );
&gt;       }
&gt; 
&gt;       public static class TestMyClass extends TestCase {
&gt;             // The setup 
&gt;             
&gt;             public void testName() {
&gt;                   //test code here
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public static Test suite() {
&gt;                   // Problem: How can I tell JUnit that
&gt;                   // the test methods are inside the inner class?
&gt;                   return new TestSuite( 
&gt; MyClass$TestMyClass.class );
&gt;             }
&gt;       }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; So, the questions are:
&gt; Can this kind of setup be done with JUnit or am I going to do 
&gt; my own test classes? Have I misunderstood how JUnit works? 
&gt; I guess that my Java knowledge still is far from expert level...
&gt; 
&gt; TIA, Santi.
